2. User Account System
Implementation: Firebase Authentication
How to build it:
Use @react-native-firebase/auth for email/password and Google OAuth sign-in
On first login, create a Firestore document under /users/{uid} storing profile data, preferences, interests, saved routes, and quest/volunteer points
Build a Preferences screen where users select interests (e.g., "music events," "food," "volunteer work," "art") — store these as an array in Firestore
Saved daily commute routes go in a subcollection /users/{uid}/commutes
Key packages:
@react-native-firebase/auth
@react-native-firebase/firestore

3. Map Integration & Custom Theming
Implementation: Google Maps Platform
How to build it:
Use react-native-maps with provider={PROVIDER_GOOGLE} and supply your Google Maps API key (enable Maps SDK for iOS/Android, Directions API, Places API, and Geocoding API in Google Cloud Console)
Apply a custom map style JSON to override the default Google Maps look — use something like Snazzy Maps or Google's Cloud-based Map Styling to create a dark or branded color theme. Pass it via the customMapStyle prop on <MapView>
For user-pinned saved places, store coordinates + label in Firestore under /users/{uid}/pins and render them as custom <Marker> components with a distinct icon
Custom overlay toggling:
Maintain a Zustand store with boolean flags: showSafety, showCommunity, showEvents, showBathrooms
A floating toggle bar at the top of the map (pill-shaped segmented control) lets the user flip these on/off
Each overlay is a separate layer of <Marker> and <Heatmap> components conditionally rendered based on the active toggles
Startup shockwave pulse (advanced):
When the map first loads at the user's location, trigger a <Circle> component that animates its radius from 0 to ~500m over 1.5 seconds using react-native-reanimated, then fades out. This is purely cosmetic but creates a nice "scanning" effect.

4. Safety Companion Feature
This is the core differentiator. It overlays safety data onto transit route options.
4a. Fetching Transit Routes
Implementation: Google Directions API (transit mode)
When the user enters an origin and destination, hit the Directions API with mode=transit and alternatives=true to get multiple route options
Parse each route's legs and steps — extract transit line names, stop sequences, departure/arrival times, and the polyline geometry
Render each route option in a bottom sheet (like Google Maps does) using @gorhom/bottom-sheet
