Normalization: Each incident record should be stored in Firestore under /incidents/{id} with a standardized schema: { type, lat, lng, timestamp, source, severity, description, geohash }. Use geohashing (via the ngeohash package) so you can efficiently query incidents near a route.
4c. Safety Score Algorithm
How to calculate it:
For each transit route returned by the Directions API, do the following:
Extract the route geometry — decode the polyline into lat/lng points
Buffer the route — for each point along the route, query Firestore for incidents within a ~300m radius using geohash range queries
Time-contextualize — weight incidents more heavily if they occurred at a similar time-of-day and day-of-week as the user's planned trip. An incident at 11pm on a Friday is more relevant if the user is traveling at 11pm on a Friday. Use a decay function: weight = 1 / (1 + daysSinceIncident * 0.1) multiplied by a time-match bonus
Aggregate — sum weighted incident counts along the route, normalize by route length, and convert to a 0–100 safety score (higher = safer). You can use a formula like: score = 100 - min(100, normalizedIncidentDensity * scalingFactor)
Display — show the score as a colored badge (green/yellow/red) next to each route option in the bottom sheet
Daily commute awareness: If the user has a saved commute, run this scoring in a scheduled Cloud Function every morning and send a push notification via Firebase Cloud Messaging if the score drops below a threshold (e.g., "Your usual L train commute has a lower safety score today due to a reported incident at 14th St–Union Square").
4d. User-Reported Incidents
Implementation:
A "Report Incident" floating action button on the map opens a modal
User selects incident type (theft, harassment, suspicious activity, medical emergency, etc.), adds optional description and photo
Submitted to Firestore under /incidents/{id} with source: "user" and verified: false
Display user-reported incidents with a distinct marker style and a label like "Community Reported — Unverified"
Verification process:
After N independent reports of the same type within X meters and Y minutes, auto-flag as "Community Verified"
Optionally, allow trusted/high-reputation users (based on quest/volunteer points) to verify reports
Moderators can review flagged reports via a simple admin panel (Firebase console or a basic web dashboard)

