6. Event Feed
Implementation:
A dedicated tab with a vertically scrolling feed mixing official NYC events, community posts, and safety alerts
Use React Query to merge and sort data from multiple Firestore collections by timestamp
Each card shows: event title, source badge (Official / Community / Safety), distance from user, time, and a thumbnail
AI-powered personalization (Gemini integration):
Use the Gemini API (generativelanguage.googleapis.com) to rank/filter feed items based on the user's stated interests and past engagement
On each feed load, send the user's interest array and the list of candidate feed items (titles + categories) to Gemini with a prompt like: "Rank these events by relevance to a user interested in [interests]. Return a JSON array of event IDs in order."
Alternatively, use Gemini to generate a brief daily digest: "Good morning! There's a free jazz concert in Prospect Park today, and your L train commute looks clear."
Recommended API: Google Gemini API (the gemini-2.0-flash model is free-tier friendly and fast)

7. Quest Feature
Implementation:
Firestore collection /quests/{id} with: { title, description, lat, lng, postedBy, claimedBy, status, reward, category, createdAt }
A "Quest Board" screen shows nearby open quests sorted by distance
Users post quests (help needed) by tapping a "Post Quest" button → fill in title, description, location, optional photo
Other users browse quests on the map (shown as special quest-pin markers) or in a list, and tap "Accept Quest" to claim it
Quest states: open → claimed → completed → verified
After completion, the quest poster confirms and the helper earns points
Points are stored in /users/{uid} and displayed on the user's profile

8. Volunteer Event Tracking & Gamification
Implementation:
Volunteer events (from NYC Open Data or user-posted) are tagged with category: "volunteer"
When a user RSVPs to a volunteer event, store it in /users/{uid}/rsvps
Geofence check-in: Use expo-location's geofencing to detect when the user arrives at the event location. When they enter the geofence, auto-check them in and award points after a minimum dwell time (e.g., 30 minutes)
Display a points leaderboard and badge system on the Profile screen: "Community Champion" (100+ points), "Neighborhood Hero" (500+ points), etc.

9. Donations
Implementation (hackathon-friendly):
For the hackathon, show a "Donate" button on community event cards that opens a modal with the intent and a placeholder UI (amount selector, payment method mockup)
If you want a functional prototype, use Stripe React Native SDK (@stripe/stripe-react-native) — create a payment intent via a Firebase Cloud Function, then present the Stripe payment sheet in-app
Donations are logged in Firestore under /donations/{id} with { userId, eventId, amount, timestamp }

10. Sponsored Events (Monetization)
Implementation:
Sponsored events are stored in /events/{id} with isSponsored: true and a sponsorName field
On the map, sponsored events get a visually distinct marker (larger, branded border, subtle glow animation)
In the feed, sponsored cards get a "Sponsored" badge and are periodically injected between organic content
For the hackathon, pre-seed a few sponsored events in Firestore and show them on the map. No payment flow needed — just demonstrate the concept in your presentation

11. Public Bathrooms Overlay
Data source: NYC Open Data has a "Directory of Toilets in Public Parks" dataset, and there's a community-maintained dataset of public restrooms. Fetch via SODA API and render as a simple icon layer on the map.

